commText: Philip Salt and Narine are at the crease. Philip Salt is on strike. Williams will open the attack
Williams to Philip Salt, FOUR, poor first delivery. Too straight - on middle and leg, Salt stays inside the line and helps it along the way to fine leg

Williams to Philip Salt, 1 run, fraction short and around off, Salt swings across the line and gets an inside edge past the stumps. Pant moves to his left and parries it to short fine where Khaleel fumbles

Williams to Narine, no ball, leg byes, 1 run, swining into Narine and he's cramped for room, the ball strikes him on the back pad outside leg-stump and rolls to the leg-side. Williams has overstepped..
Free-hit coming up
Williams to Philip Salt, wide, sprays a full toss down leg, Salt gets inside the line and can't connect, wide called and the free-hit stays

Williams to Philip Salt, SIX, Salt makes the most of the free-hit. Turning into a poor start for Williams, already 14 runs and just 3 balls bowled. This is a length ball right in the slot, Salt heaves across the line and sends it sailing over deep mid-wicket
Williams to Philip Salt, FOUR, I0$ back of a length around off, Salt punches it on the rise and places it in front of square on the off-side. This shot indicates that the ball is coming on nicely..
Williams to Philip Salt, leg byes, 1 run, I0$ nips back in, Salt misses the tuck and the ball deflects off the pad

Williams to Narine, FOUR, ordinary first over and KKR are off to a flier. Short ball and Narine is rushed on the pull, but he still goes through with the shot and pulls it behind square on the leg-side, one bounce and over the ropes
Khaleel Ahmed, left-arm fast medium, comes into the attack

Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, 2 runs, dropped! Williams has had a shocking 7 balls. He's given 23 in the first over and now has dropped Salt. I0$ full pitcher and Salt miscues the loft straight up, Williams settles under it near mid-on and goes reverse cup, but the ball bursts through and hits him on the shoulder before going down
Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, no run, good length ball around off, Salt defends to the off-side

Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, no run, now strays down leg, Salt stands his ground and misses the glance. Wide called and Pant decides to review, UltraEdge shows a spike as ball is next to the pad. Decision overturned
Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, no run, I0$ full pitcher outside off, Salt creams the drive straight to cover-point
Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, 2 runs, I0$ on a length and angled across, Salt tucks it through the vacant mid-wicket region and picks up a brace
Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, no run, I0$ very full and in the blockhole, Salt digs it out to cover and Khaleel walks up to have a word
Williams to Narine, no run, full and cramping Narine, he clears his front leg and attempts the flick, the ball sneaks between his legs
Williams to Narine, 1 run, I0$ fullish delivery, Narine mistimes the drive in front of mid-off and quickly crosses over
Williams to Philip Salt, no run, I0$ slower short of length delivery, Salt is through the pull early and gets an inside edge onto the body
Williams to Philip Salt, SIX, very small margins for error. Williams goes full and Salt pumps him down the ground, minimal followthrough of the bat and it is all hands as the ball soars over long-off

Williams to Philip Salt, SIX, back to back sixes. Williams feeling the heat. The length is again full but the line is on middle, Salt clears his front leg and uses his bottom hand to whip it over cow corner. 94-meter six..

Williams to Philip Salt, no run, I0$ fraction short and Salt swings across the line, but the ball does not bounce and sneaks past the under-edge, not far from the stumps either and bounces on the way to Pant
Khaleel from round the wicket
Khaleel Ahmed to Narine, no run, I0$ bouncer on the stumps, Narine ducks and allows it to sail over
Khaleel Ahmed to Narine, 1 run, high full toss below the waist, Narine swings it away to deep backward square
Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, no run, I0$ back of a length on middle, Salt knocks it to cover-point
Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, no run, I0$ slower ball outside off, Salt is through the loft early and does not connect

Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, FOUR, I0$ off-pace delivery and had a bit of width, Salt flays it uppishly and just manages to get it over the extra cover region. Once it is passed the infield there's no chance chasing that
Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, 1 run, another high full toss that Khaleel gets away with, Salt heaves and gets it high on the bat, the ball rolls to mid-wicket
Rasikh Dar Salam, right-arm medium, comes into the attack
Rasikh Salam to Philip Salt, 1 run, I0$ good length ball around off, Salt makes room and punches it towards cover
Pant was standing up to the stumps for Salt. He's gone back for Narine
Rasikh Salam to Narine, FOUR, slower ball but Narine had the room outside off, he throws his bat and toe-ends it over extra cover
Rasikh goes round the wicket
Rasikh Salam to Narine, FOUR, high full toss outside off, Narine stays leg-side and slashes it square on the off-side. Another delivery that was very close to being a no-ball
Rasikh Salam to Narine, 1 run, slower short of length delivery, Narine mistimes the pull wide of mid-wicket and long-on tiidies up
Pant back up to the stumps

Rasikh Salam to Philip Salt, FOUR, back of a length outside off, Salt stands tall and thumps it on the rise over extra cover. This is top class hitting. Pant walks up and puts his hand over Rasikh's shoulder, has a word with him
Rasikh Salam to Philip Salt, 1 run, angled into the pads, Salt flicks to deep mid-wicket and retains strike
This is the fifth 50+ opening partnership between Salt & Narine is the most by a pair this seaosn. One more than by Rohit & Ishan KIshan.
Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, no run, I0$ good length ball on leg, Salt defends to cover

Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, FOUR, this was not a bad delivery. I0$ short of length delivery and very little width on offer, Salt stays leg-side and flays it in front of square, luckily he finds the gap in a packed off-side field and the ball races away
Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, no run, off-pace delivery and Salt is early into the pull, toe-ends it to mid-wicket
Goes round the wicket

Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, SIX, fifty for Salt. He just loves batting at Eden Gardens. Even gets a thumbs up from owner SRK. He was dropped early on and has made Delhi pay for it. Full pitcher around off, right in the arc for Salt and he pumps it over long-off. Pumps his chest, points a finger at someone and then raises his bat to celebrate the landmark. The ball has been lost and the fourth umpire has come out with a box balls
Back over the wicket
Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, FOUR, the boundaries continue flow.. Full toss around off, Salt slices it with an open face and the ball races away behind square on the off-side
Khaleel Ahmed to Philip Salt, FOUR .. and again. Khaleel sticks to the low full toss ploy outside off, Salt opens the bat face intentionally and slices it right between backward point and short third

Timeout! The new ball and powerplay were imporant and this is why, these two have taken the game away in that first six overs. Williams dropped Salt when he was on 15 and the Englishman has made the most of it. The asking rate is below run-a-ball and this should be a cake walk from here.

Powerplay summary -- Salt gets KKR off to a flier -- Williams goes for 23 in the first over -- Salt dropped on 15 by Williams (1.1) -- Rasikh goes for 15 in his first over -- 50-run opening stand comes up in just 4.2 overs -- Salt brings up fifty off 26 balls -- Khaleel goes for 18 in his third over
Axar Patel, Left arm orthodox, comes into the attack
Axar to Narine, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Axar to Narine, out Caught by Fraser-McGurk!! A wicket first ball for Axar. A flat length delivery and Narine swung that straight to the fielder at deep mid-wicket. Simple chance and Fraser-McGurk makes no mistake. Can this spark something for DC? Narine c Fraser-McGurk b Axar 15(10) [4s-3]

A short of length delivery that hurries Rinku Singh on the pull, he did not know much about it, the top-edge carries to third man and Kuldeep judges it well. Three quick wickets and suddenly DC can hope for something of a miracle. Rinku Singh c Kuldeep Yadav b Williams 11(11) [4s-1]

22:59 Local Time, 17:29 GMT, 22:59 IST: Easy chase for KKR. At the toss, Pant said the pitch was dry and that it would help the spinners. It sure did but DC did not help themselves as they made just 153 and the two spinners they had had not much to defend. Salt at the top ensured that the game was half-complete with his blistering assault. That innings set KKR on the way and despite DC pulling things back with three wickets, the two Iyers took their side home. KKR could have won earlier but the Iyers batted sensibly after three losses and did not give DC any chance to come back into the game. A totally different game this to the one that PBKS chased down 261 here last time but DC threw away their wickets and a bit more discipline shown could have given them more runs. KKR stay on 2nd with this win. Stay tuned for the presentation...

Rishabh Pant | DC captain: It was a good option to bat first. As a batting unit we didn't bat well, 150 was below par with how things were going. But we learn from our mistakes, every day is not your day. The way we were going as a team was nice (winning 4 out of their last 5 games), but these games come along in T20s. I think anything around 180-210 would have been a good score, we didn't give our bowlers enough runs to defend.

Salt: Good to be contributing. Have had a good run in the home games. Nice that we've had continuity in conditions. Coming from the last game, to put in a performance like that from the bowlers, really pleased for them. It is high risk at times, but it's about putting the odds in your favour. Have to keep backing yourself and make those right options. It does (good keeping performance helps confidence?). Very helpful keeping first and see what it's doing. Gives an advantage in assessing conditions first. Sunil keeps things simple but he's a deep thinker about the game. We've dovetailed nicely in this competition. If one of us gets going, we feed the strike to them.

Shreyas Iyer | KKR captain: [on if the pitch would play this way?] Not at all. Considering the last few matches, 200 was a par score. After the powerplay the pitch started helping the spinners, was tacky. We got a fair idea as to how it played and to tackle the tackiness. Narine still does not attend those meetings but Salt is always there, gives us his inputs and it's pure bliss to see him coming up and doing all this. [if Narine attends meetings] He doesn't. I would not recommend him to come either. [on Chakaravarthy] he has not been at his best the last few games. He has been assessing the wicket and has been giving us inputs. The way he turned up today was simply brilliant. [qualification] We have always been looking at it, even from the first game. The mindset is to qualify as early as possible. Just work on our work ethic and processes, don't want to look at the points table.

Varun Chakaravarthy | Player of the Match: It was holding a bit, as the game progressed in the 2nd innings, it was turning as well. [on him having a good match-up against Pant] Nothing like that, when the catch was dropped, I felt that was a better ball, and the one I got him, on other grounds, it would have gone for a six. Cricket has become a game of fine margins. I liked Tristan Stubbs' wicket. I planned to bowl the legspinner to him and it worked out. [on conversations between him and Narine] Silence. When something doesn't work for me, he is always there. In the last game after conceding so many runs, it was a tough pill to take but the whole team motivated us. Abhishek Nayar and even Shahrukh Khan came and spoke to me, definitely motivated us. [on the cheerleaders dancing] They should start dancing only for the sixers and not for the fours.

KKR turned up on a pitch that aided their spinners while DC got it wrong maybe even from the toss. Was definitely not a bat-first pitch. On that note we sign off from here. Do come back here for all your cricketing fix. Until next time, take care, be well, sleep tight and cuddle well. Bye.
